Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the US government represents an enormous bailout for the creditors of these institutions, whose losses have been inflated further in the face of falling house prices.
Now that the government is taking on Fannie's and Freddie's debts in its entirety, American taxpayers will have to pay for everything that the creditors' insufficient financial means were unable to cover.
Why such a rescue action in the most unapologetically capitalist country in the world?
Do not the ancient principles of capitalism include that those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that now innocent taxpayers have to bear the consequences of their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be apparent if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly outlined.
But they are not.
Mostly, it is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost US taxpayers in the end. It may prevent further systemic effects that would force the financial sector and thus the global economy to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify, one cannot conclude that they do not exist.
In addition, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely seen as being backed by an implicit guarantee of the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a rescue action by the US government could undermine confidence in government bonds – and by association in other financial instruments.
The problems extend far beyond the US economy.
The world economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative highs and crashes in asset values, which bring questions of trust, but also fairness, into the equation.
Similarly, in many other countries, the housing sector is now ending its high-flying phase, and they may face the same pains – and the same moral dilemmas – as the US economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem is not just the housing markets.
The stock markets are that as well.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose between 2005 and 2007 by a factor of 5 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose between 2003 and 2007 real by a factor of 5 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar highs and crashes on the stock markets have occurred in many other countries.
Solange they held, the prior boom phases led to overheating of these economies.
Now, since they have turned around, a loss of confidence could seize the world economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary – not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people react when, in the face of collapsing markets, aid is withheld.
The people's reactions to these events depend on their feelings and sense of justice.
The described highs and crashes have caused a great redistribution of wealth.
Whoever invested in the stock market or on the housing market did well or poorly depending on the timing.
The people will judge the fairness of these results based on what they were told and the implicit promises they derived from it.
What was told to people in all these countries about the markets into which they invested their money?
Was everything really true?
Es gibt leider keinen Weg, das herauszufinden.
Die Politik kann lediglich allgemein reagieren und nicht alle Fälle einzeln behandeln.
We know that the economic growth of recent years in many countries was spectacular.
But were investments in their markets sold too cheaply?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere lured people into believing that boom times would bring prosperity for all?
Sicher ist, dass, obwohl es eine Menge „billiges Geschwätz“ – allgemeine Ratschläge unter Vorbehalt – gegeben haben mag, the majority of losers in this game will not go hungry.
However, we cannot carelessly conclude that we should leave all their losses without restriction.
The nagging problem is one of "good faith".
Economies flourish only when "good faith" prevails.
The current situation, in which speculative highs have driven the global economy – and are now, after their collapse, driving it into recession – suggests that people who sold certain investments have acted in bad faith.
Let us take the investors who bought Fannie and Freddie's bonds.
Although the US government never officially promised to bail them out, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to evaluate their strength in an annual report.
This agency, however, never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The government's top officials never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that the investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could that be fair?
The world is now discovering that capitalism and its power to transform economies.
However, capitalism is based on trust.
An unfair treatment can be fatal for economic growth, because it means that people lose faith in companies and are therefore less willing to provide them with their valuable capital and labor.
Is such a result morally preferable to a bailout?
